:INFO
Why Wood Species Matters
Not all woods carve equally. For spoon carving the most important qualities are \
straight grain, moderate hardness, and low tendency to split unpredictably. Green \
(freshly cut) wood of almost any species is workable, but some are far more \
pleasant than others. Toxic or tainting species must be avoided for eating utensils.

:PATH
Birch
Silver birch and downy birch are the gold standard for beginner spoon carving
|
:INFO
Birch
Silver birch and downy birch are the gold standard for beginner spoon carving in \
northern Europe. The grain is fine and even, the wood is light-colored, and it carves \
cleanly in all directions. Fresh birch is almost effortless with a sharp knife. It

:PATH
Cherry and Apple
Fruit woods are denser than birch and require a sharper knife and more patient
|
:INFO
Cherry and Apple
Fruit woods are denser than birch and require a sharper knife and more patient cutting, \
but they reward the effort. Cherry has a warm reddish-brown tone that deepens with age \
and oil. Apple is fine-grained and creamy white with occasional pink streaks.

:PATH
Alder
Alder is underrated for spoon carving.
|
:INFO
Alder
Alder is underrated for spoon carving. It is soft, light, and carves quickly with \
minimal grain tearout. The color is a pale pinkish-tan that dries to a quiet cream. It \
is common across wet and riparian habitats and often available as coppice or windfall

:PATH
Woods to Avoid
Yew is beautiful but toxic: do not use it for eating utensils.
|
:INFO
Woods to Avoid
Yew is beautiful but toxic: do not use it for eating utensils. Black locust (false \
acacia) and most tropical hardwoods are too dense to carve comfortably with a knife \
alone. Elder has an unpleasant smell when cut. Oak and ash are workable but

:NOTE
Sourcing Green Wood
The best green wood comes from freshly felled trees, coppiced branches, or storm \
blowdowns. A branch of 8 to 12 cm diameter is ideal for splitting into spoon \
blanks. Contact local tree surgeons, parks departments, or community orchards. \
Many are happy to give away fresh cuttings that would otherwise go to chip. \
Avoid wood that has been sitting on the ground for more than a few weeks as it \
will already have begun to dry and crack.

:QUOTE
The wood tells you what to make. Your job is to listen carefully and remove \
everything that is not a spoon.
